 do with this variant. Pure aggression for when you wish to layeth the smackdown on some gutless punks in style. No mercy.<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> basically, heavily unbalanced variant.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> (ii)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Standard variant - Level range restrictions, but no class or equipment restrictions.<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> standard variant.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> (iii)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Standardised equipment variant - level range restriction with a standardised equipment list for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> all</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> classes.<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> balanced standardised equipment list will hopefully ensure a contest based on the relative skill of the protagonists.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Note: some classes are more stat driven (equipment dependent) than others. To take this into account, we could mix and match variants i.e. Standardised equipment variant with class restrictions<br><br>e.g. warrior A in full banded with weapon vs warrior B in full banded with weapon.<br><br>These guidelines are fast and loose, encouraged to bring forth more ideas and contributions. The most fundamental precepts are that (i) any rule-subset is agreed upon by the participants, and that (ii) all contests are adjudicated in a fair and impartial manner.<br><br>Right, do we have any contenders? <br><br>Regards,<br>Riotgirl [Eliza Dushku Form] Hard Woman Enchanter<br><br>&quot;she's like this cleavagey, slut-bomb walking around going 'oh, check me out. i'm wicked cool. i'm five by five'<br><br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=riotgirl>riotgirl</A> at: 2/4/02 7:21:34 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=riotgirl>riotgirl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elite Poster</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(2/4/02 7:15:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=886.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Germination Of An Idea</span><hr size=1> Many, many years ago, I used to play in a game with a restricted PvP environment. PvP took the game to another level, pitting one's skill and cunning against another player. The adrenaline rush when you killed another player was simply <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> incredible</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. My first ever PK (player kill) left me in trembling, convulsive state unable to type for at least half an hour. Other players were known to have left the computer lab for a smoke to calm themselves down.<br><br>It was a completely different experience to playing any number of FPS (Doom, Quake, Unreal Tournament, Counter-Strike etc ..) on a frag server. The gameplay was far more complex, and just as frantic but in a different way. PKing required a different set of skills than those demanded in FPS.<br><br>My first and subsquently last duel in EQ was in Steamfront, playing my level 9 (at that time) Druid alt. I had just zoned from Lfay with an acquaintance of mine when an Iksar Monk came running up to us, interrupting our conversation by inquiring if we would like to duel. At first, we turned down his offer and prepared to continue on our way. Then I received the system message, '/player x has challenged you to a duel!'. For one, brief moment a whole new, unexplored world opened up before me and I accepted the duel.<br><br>It was not a classic contest by any means due to our relative low levels and inexperience. My tactics consisted of snaring, DDing and then meleeing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> without</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a damage shield. Yep, I was incredibly wet behind the ears, and a complete novice to the world of PvP. The contest ended when I eventually zoned, and my rival and I congratulated each other for an exciting (well, to us at least) contest that provided an hithero undiscovered sense of excitement.<br><br>Myself and Gribble did toy with the idea of creating characters on a PvP server, before dismissing the idea out of hand. Simply put, it would be futile to even bother when you instinctively <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> know</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that you're going to get repeatedly gang-banged (jumped by a group when in a precarious position) and spawn camped/killed. Rules or no rules, didn't seem like my idea of a particularly exciting experience. Also, the initial thrill of powergaming wears off rather too quickly.<br><br>After reading Zehn's thread, 'Fight Club' seemed like the logical conclusion. What better way to resolve those grudges by challenging your opponent to a duel, based on an established rule-set and watched over by your peers for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> maximum</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bragging rights! Think of 'Gladiator', think of 'Fight Club', think of all the money that can be made if one possesses an entrepreneurial spirit i.e. offering gambling odds on contests.<br><br>If nothing else, this has allowed me to put to use a previously accidental post.<br><br>Regards,<br>Riotgirl [Eliza Dushku Form] Hard Woman Enchanter<br><br>&quot;she's like this cleavagey, slut-bomb walking around going 'oh, check me out. i'm wicked cool. i'm five by five'<br><br><br><br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=riotgirl>riotgirl</A> at: 2/4/02 8:06:20 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=riotgirl>riotgirl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elite Poster</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(2